 grade‚Üê(compare Sort)nodes;starting;pass;swapped;count;i
‚çù Use the given comparison function to sort the node IDs into their proper order.
‚çù This is generally used on quite small lists, so we'll use a Bubble Sort for code simplicity.
‚çù The Bubble Sort typically has O(n¬≤) time & comparison complexity.
‚çù (The algorithm can be changed to something more complicated if optimization is needed later.)
‚çù ‚àácompare: Produce +1 if [1]>[2], ¬Ø1 if [1]<[2], or 0 if [1]=[2]; numerically: -/[1 2]

 starting‚Üênodes ‚çù The starting order of the node numbers, for use in building the final grade-ordering

 :For pass :In ‚ç≥¬Ø1+count‚Üê‚â¢nodes ‚çù Loop through passes, with each pass being shorter than the previous one
     swapped‚Üê0 ‚çù Has anything been swapped in this pass or not (so we can tell if we're done early)?
     :For i :In ‚ç≥count-pass ‚çù Check each item-pair [i+0 1] to see if they need swapping
         :If 1=compare nodes[i+0 1] ‚ãÑ nodes[i+0 1]‚Üênodes[i+1 0] ‚ãÑ swapped‚Üê1 ‚ãÑ :EndIf ‚çù If they're out-of-order, swap them
     :EndFor
     :If ~swapped ‚ãÑ :Leave ‚ãÑ :EndIf ‚çù If nothing got swapped during this pass, then we're done sorting
 :EndFor

 grade‚Üêstarting‚ç≥nodes ‚çù Turn the final order into a ‚çã-vector
